caption: Figure 1: Overview of the M³-Impute model.
description: The figure provides a detailed illustration of the M³-Impute model architecture, outlining the key components and their interactions.  It begins with the input data matrix, which is then converted into a bipartite graph. A Graph Neural Network (GNN) is used to generate node embeddings for the samples and features. These embeddings are further processed by the Feature Correlation Unit (FCU) and Sample Correlation Unit (SCU), which explicitly model feature-wise and sample-wise correlations, respectively.  Finally, a Multi-layer Perceptron (MLP) combines the outputs from FCU and SCU to predict the missing feature values. The legend clearly defines the symbols and connections within the diagram, enhancing its readability.

caption: Figure 1: Overview of the M³-Impute model.
description: The figure provides a visual overview of the M³-Impute model architecture.  It shows the data input (a matrix with missing values, represented as N/A), the creation of a bipartite graph representing the data, the use of a Graph Neural Network (GNN) to generate embeddings for samples and features, and the introduction of a novel Feature Correlation Unit (FCU) and Sample Correlation Unit (SCU) to model feature-wise and sample-wise correlations respectively.  Finally, it illustrates the use of a Multi-Layer Perceptron (MLP) to predict the missing values. The legend clearly defines the symbols and data flow within the diagram.

caption: Figure 3: Model performance vs. missing ratios. MAE scores are offset by HyperImpute [23].
description: This figure shows the performance comparison of M³-Impute and other imputation methods under different missing ratios (0.1, 0.3, 0.5, and 0.7). The MAE scores are offset by the MAE of HyperImpute for better visualization. The results demonstrate the effectiveness of M³-Impute across various missing ratios, especially in datasets with complex feature correlations.
